{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ceb83fa6-13d8-4a8b-800e-95ccc38537a2","content":"PID 12345 doesn't exist on this machine. No worries — here's how to do both steps yourself:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Determine CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n\nRun these checks against your actual PID:\n\n```bash\n# Check if the process has loaded libcoreclr.so (CoreCLR)\ncat /proc/<PID>/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Not CoreCLR\"\n\n# Check if it's a fully self-contained native binary (NativeAOT)\n# NativeAOT apps won't load libcoreclr.so and are statically compiled\nfile /proc/<PID>/exe\n```\n\n| Signal | Runtime |\n|--------|---------|\n| `libcoreclr.so` in memory maps | **CoreCLR** |\n| No `libcoreclr.so`, `file` shows a standard ELF binary | **NativeAOT** |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Configure crash dumps\n\n#### For CoreCLR apps\n\nSet these environment variables (e.g. in your systemd unit or shell):\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # Enable dumps on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # Full dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t  # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n#### For NativeAOT apps\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the CoreCLR dump infrastructure. Use the **kernel core dump** mechanism instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern\necho \"/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\" | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core file size limit for the process\nulimit -c unlimited\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n#### For either runtime (systemd service)\n\nIf your app runs as a systemd service, you can also use `systemd-coredump`:\n\n```ini\n# In your .service file\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR**: Check `/proc/<PID>/maps` for `libcoreclr` — if present, use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`; if absent (NativeAOT), use kernel `core_pattern` + `ulimit -c unlimited`. Both approaches require a process restart to take effect.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0b2b6ebc-a50e-413f-857b-c62d175cc0b0","outputTokens":689,"requestId":"DA0E:32F277:591F6B:65AADE:6A03DA02"},"id":"54c5c715-92b7-480b-894e-212058ee2c6c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:55:29.453Z","parentId":"a9ecdc87-00bc-409b-b5b5-ca05baa3161a"}
